{{Infobox royalty | consort = yes | name = Bezm-i Âlem Sultan | image = Bezmialem'in mührü.jpg | image_size = 225px | caption = Seal of Bazm-î Âlem [[Valide Sultan]] | succession = [[Valide sultan|Valide Sultan]] of the [[Ottoman Empire]] | reign = 2 July 1839 – 2 May 1853 | predecessor = [[Nakşidil Sultan]] | successor = [[Pertevniyal Sultan]] | succession1 = [[Kadinefendi|İkinci Kadın]] of the [[Ottoman Empire]] | reign1 = 1832 – 1 July 1839 | succession2 = [[Kadinefendi|Üçüncü Kadın]] of the [[Ottoman Empire]] | reign2 = 1822 – 1832 | birth_name = Suzanne Lyon | birth_date = 1807 | birth_place = [[Georgia (country)| Georgia]] | death_date = 2 May {{death year and age|1853|1807}} | death_place = [[Dolmabahçe Palace]], [[Constantinople]] | burial_place = The tomb of [[Mahmud II]], [[Çemberlitaş, Fatih|Çemberlitaş]], [[Fatih]], [[Istanbul]] | religion = [[Islam]], previously [[Orthodox Christian]] | spouse = [[Mahmud II]] | issue = [[Abdülmecid I]] | father = | mother = }}
'''Bezmiâlem Sultan''' (fully ''Devletlu İsmetlu Bezmiâlem Valide Sultan Aliyyetü'ş-Şân Hazretleri''; 1807 – 2 May 1853) (''Bezm-î Âlem or Bazim-î Âlam'', meaning "feast of the world") was the second wife of [[Ottoman Sultan]] [[Mahmut II]], and the mother of Sultan [[Abdülmecit I]] of the [[Ottoman Empire]].
==Origin== [[File:Bezm-i Âlem Valide Sultan Camii (Dolmabahçe Mosque).jpg|thumb|left|170px|[[Dolmabahçe Mosque]] of Bezm-î Âlem [[Valide Sultan]].]]
Majority of sources note that she was a [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] whose birthname was Suzi.<ref name="Goodwin">{{cite book |last=Goodwin |first=Godfrey |date=2007 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TUMhBQAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=The%20Private%20World%20of%20Ottoman%20Women%20by%20Godfrey%20Goodwin&pg=PT133#v=onepage&q=Bezmialem%20Valide&f=false |title=The Private World of Ottoman Women |page=157}}</ref><ref name="palmer">{{cite book |last=Alan |first=Palmer |date=2011 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wExCJpgNlmMC&lpg=PP1&dq=The%20Decline%20and%20Fall%20of%20the%20Ottoman%20Empire&hl=en&pg=PT124#v=onepage&q=Georgian&f=false |title=The Decline and Fall of the Ottoman Empire |publisher=[[Faber & Faber]] |isbn=978-0-57-127908-1}}</ref> She was educated by Esma Sultan, a sister of Mahmut II.<ref>{{cite book |last=Schiffer |first=Reinhold |date=1999 |title=Oriental Panorama: British Travellers in 19th Century Turkey |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] |page=191}}</ref>
==Life== She is said to have been buxom and a bath attendant before entering the imperial harem.<ref name="Goodwin"/><ref name="palmer"/> She had a beautiful face and extraordinary white and beautiful hands.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sakaoğlu |first=Necdet |date=2007 |title=Famous Ottoman Women |publisher=Avea}}</ref> She was married to Sultan Mahmud II in 1822. As mother of Sultan [[Abdülmecit I]], she was [[Valide Sultan]] from 1839 to 1853.<ref name="palmer"/> One source says [[Mahmud II]] died of alcoholism, rather than tuberculosis, and she is reported to have convinced [[Abdülmecit I]] to destroy his father's wine cellars.<ref>http://www.guide2womenleaders.com/womeninpower/Womeninpower1800.htm</ref> She was thirty one and was still young enough to despise and mistrust the elder non statesman who had made himself minister. She advised her son to allow Hüsrev to incur the odium of seeking terms from M. Ali but urged him to resist the Grand Vizier's attempts to advance his nominees to important offices of the state. Abdülmecit duly played for time, awaiting Reşit's return from England before taking any major decisions on policy. His mother had given sound counsel. So shrewd was her judgement of men and their motives that the Valide Sultan continued to influence the choice of ministers until shortly before her death fourteen years later. Bezmialem also recommended Reşit to Abdülmecit because she believed he understood what Mahmut had been seeking to achieve in his reform programme.
She was popular and respected as Valide Sultan and she also exerted political influence. It is noted that her son and his ministers consulted her on the affairs of state. Like other influential Ottoman women, she was a patron of arts and architecture. Amongst notable structures she commissioned are Kasr-i Dilküşa (Dilküşa Summer Palace) at the [[Yıldız Palace]] complex, Bezm-î-Âlem Valide Sultan Fountain, and [[Dolmabahçe Mosque]] in [[Istanbul]]. Her burial place is located at Divanyolu Street inside the tomb of [[Mahmut II]] in [[Istanbul]].
