{{Infobox Officeholder |name = Roberto V. Pesqueira |image = Roberto_V_Pesqueira.jpg |imagesize = |alt = |caption = |office1 = Federal Deputy of Mexico |term_start1 = 1913 |term_end1 = 1913 |predecessor1 = |successor1 = |constituency1 = District 1, Sonora<ref name="dict-sonora" /> |term_start2 = 1917 |term_end2 = ? |predecessor2 = |successor2 = |constituency2 = |birth_date = 1882 |birth_place = [[Arizpe, Sonora]]<ref name="dict-sonora">{{cite book|last=Almada|first=Francisco R.|title=Diccionario de historia, geografía y biografía sonorenses|publisher=Gobierno de Sonora|location=Hermosillo, Mexico|year=1983|url=http://enciclopedia.sonora.gob.mx/Runscript.asp?p=ASP\pg353.asp&page=353|accessdate=2009-12-07|language=Spanish}}</ref> |death_date = {{death year and age|1966|1882}} |death_place = |restingplace = |restingplacecoordinates = |nationality = Mexican |party = Anti-Reelectionist Party (1911)<ref name="dict-sonora" /> |otherparty = <!--For additional political affiliations--> |spouse = |relations = [[Ignacio L. Pesqueira]] (brother)<ref name="Cumberland" />{{Rp|72}} |children = |alma_mater = |occupation = |committees = |religion = |footnotes = }}
'''Roberto V. Pesqueira Morales''' (1882 &ndash; 1966) was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] politician who was elected twice to the [[Chamber of Deputies (Mexico)|Chamber of Deputies]] and was commissioned by President [[Venustiano Carranza]] to work as a confidential agent in the [[United States]] and secure [[diplomatic recognition]] to his regime.<ref name="Barragan">{{cite book|last=Barragán Rodríguez|first=Juan|title=Historia del ejército y de la revolución constitucionalista|publisher=Antigua Librería Robredo|location=Mexico City|year=1946| volume=1 |pages=135–140 |accessdate=2009-12-07 |language=Spanish}}</ref>
Pesqueira was born in [[Arizpe, Sonora]]. His older brother, [[Ignacio L. Pesqueira|Ignacio]], went on to serve as [[Governor of Sonora]].<ref name="Cumberland">{{cite book|last=Cumberland|first=Charles Curtis|title=Mexican Revolution: the Constitutionalist years|publisher=University of Texas Press|location=Austin, TX, USA|year=1972|series=Texas Pan American series|volume=4|isbn=9780292750005|oclc=123321124|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D8YQd9hsne0C&pg=PA72&dq=Roberto+V.+Pesqueira|accessdate=2009-12-07}}</ref>{{Rp|72}} Roberto joined [[Francisco I. Madero]]'s Anti-Reelectionist Party in 1910 and was elected federal deputy representing the first district of Sonora in 1913,<ref name="dict-sonora" /> but refused to serve in the Chamber of Deputies after the consummation of [[Victoriano Huerta]]'s {{lang|fr|[[Decena trágica|coup d'état]]}} on 20 February 1913, and decided to join the revolutionary forces instead.<ref name="Cumberland" />{{Rp|58}}
He was elected federal deputy once again in 1917 and acquired [[oil field]]s some years later. In February 1923 he wrote a letter to President [[Álvaro Obregón]], alerting him of some irregularities detected in his foreign competitors; in particular, the Huasteca Oil Company.<ref name="Hall">{{cite book|last=Hall|first=Linda B.|title=Oil, Banks, and Politics: The United States and Postrevolutionary Mexico|publisher=University of Texas Press|location=Austin, TX, USA|year=1995|page=123|isbn=9780292731011|oclc=231655743|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9PIW33ecHvMC&pg=RA1-PA123&dq=Roberto+V.+Pesqueira|accessdate=2009-12-07}}</ref>
